76561197960552318,Not Recommended,288470,12074433,"Posted: 12 September, 2014",all,Chrome Badger,"If you want Fable, go back to the original plus Lost Chapters.I loved the original Fable, but this port is not worth the extra money. When first announced, I was excited because I thought they'd improve upon the original. Fix issues with the old one, gameplay or glitch wise, maybe add in a couple new quests, and fix the bad user interface and player menus.Instead, it's really only a graphical difference. Worse yet, the graphics aren't really that much better. Sure, they smoothed things up and fixed up some lighting effects, but the models (especially the faces) are ugly as sin. I was hoping (more than anything else) they'd take a page from Fable 2 & 3, and give the option to buy a house without killing the occupants. Instead, it looks like that's still the plan. At least they looked at the menu options. Well, they looked but they did not fix. In fact, they made them worse. I bought this game for the PC, I WANT TO USE A KEYBOARD AND MOUSE. You cannot rebind keys. The default Keyboard/Mouse keys I cannot imagine are good for a right-handed player. For a left-handed player like myself, they're murder. The menu is horribly clunky. If I want an to equip a sword, for example. Imagine I've already navigated the maze of menu options to get there. Then, to actually equip the sword, you don't push enter. you push A. ON THE KEYBOARD. If you want to go back? B. The letter B. Not escape, that won't work.Yes, I know controllers are available that work with my PC. I don't want them, I'm comfortable with my keyboard and mouse. As a big fan of Fable games (I own them all) this is insulting. The graphics are softer. The cutscenes still look like they're from the original (pixels EVERYWHERE). There's no customization to how I want to play a game that's all about customization. The User Interface is worse than before. There's a stupid book opening animation that has to play everytime you open the game or want to exit back to menu. This is a horrible addition to the Fable family. I'll probably play it again, I paid for it. Don't make the same mistake.EDIT: Upon assistance from another player, he revealed that you actually need to be on your sepcific character before the option to change controls appears. While this provides immense relief, left-handed players may be distraught to discover you cannot rebind end, delete, pgdn or pgup, home or insert. Further, the numberpad keys cannot be assigned to the hotbar keys.Still, I count this as a victory, and a lot of my stress about the game has been removed."
76561198116527414,Recommended,288470,28291542,"Posted: 10 December, 2016",all,Sigmar,"This game has a very specific character. On the one hand, it displays a dorky, sometimes childish type of humor (fart joke level), on the other hand, it gets really dark at certain points: I am talking about villains slaughtering helpless civilians, torturing children and murdering hostages in front of your eyes.There are summarizing scenes at the end of each story chapter in a seriously epic tone, presenting you as the heir of a mysterious power and saviour of the world from the rule of demons and the undead. In contrast to that, you can donate books to a school and watch the little ones recite the lines on stage, giggling at the mature content, or you can go to the beach and participate in a competition called Chicken Kickin' (yes, the name is a literal description!). And it is not just comic relief, the overall atmosphere, at least for the most part, is playful and self-ironic. Slay an ugly monster, then take its head, go to the next town, and run around showing it to everyone to enjoy the applause. Choose a fabulous nom-de-guerre, like ""Liberator"" or ""The Hood"", and listen to everyone you see talking about you until you cannot even hear it yourself anymore. Find a sick child in the poor quarter of a town, learn that you need certain mushrooms to save it - then get one of those by performing a Russian style dance number in front of a woman to make her laugh and give you the shroom as  a reward... These examples should give you an idea of the vibe.The production value is undeniably excellent: The artstyle is captivating and flawlessly executed, in all departments from graphics (both environment and animations) via sound (atmospheric and beautiful music, the voice acting always top-notch!) to the writing (actually interesting lore-texts,  diversified quests with creative solutions and twists) - I feel that a lot of love went into these aspects.The character development I find a little unbalanced. You have access to high level gear pretty early, and then, armour and weapons don't change that much any longer. Other games have succeeded to give you more intermediate goals to work for. Also, it does not help that the title everybody knows you under (like ""Liberator"") is not earned by heroic deeds, but purchased from a trader after you have become tired of hearing your default title all the time (""Chicken Chaser""). Nevertheless, I appreciate that you see your hero growing up from his traumatic childhood experience via the training as a youngling (which is, at the same time, the tutorial thus integrated in your personal story - kudos to whomever had that idea!) to the point where you are a grown man and a famous hero in the end. This organic development of your story is a big plus.There are a few annoying things though:- The inventory is divided into different parts and subparts, which makes sense somehow, but you need many clicks and scrolls when you want to find a specific consumable or tool.- NPCs are only available during a limited part of the game day, and there is no ""wait x hours"" function, which makes you run around and look for some public mattress with a suspicious blanket to sleep in - it is not only kind of ""ew"" and underwhelming, it is a lot of unnecessary running.- Some quests give you too little choices; e.g. I wanted to complete the game as a noble hero, including the charitable task of collecting books for the local school - but you cannot do that legally, you have to steal certain books from the houses of people who just welcomed you with cheers of love and admiration; that bothered me a little.- There are too many loading screens!- Also, I never like it when enemies respawn endlessly, it belittles the achievement of having defeated those enemies before and encourages farming - a technical, non-immersive form of playing an RPG. But that is a matter of taste.The combat is not very well designed in my opinion. It is interesting for a while, specifically when you are still discovering all the new types of enemies, but after the waves of identical opponents in the Arena quest, you have seen (almost) everything and can only expect repetitions of the same patterns while you mash your buttons. The most annoying thing about the whole game though is the ease with which enemies stagger you, even if you parry and wear heavy armour. Some types like trolls, nymphs and the final enemy of the main quest send you to the ground every few seconds (!) because they spam unblockable power attacks from a distance. That does not feel good, you don't feel powerful and heroic at this point, and you don't feel well entertained either when you constantly watch your toon picking himself up. I think this is a cheap way of adding artificial difficulty and takes away from the immersion and the fun.Still, there are many features to enjoy: Minigames within the game like the aforementioned Chicken Kickin' or the numerous cardgames in the taverns, the various demon door riddles you can solve for bonus loot, or the challenge to buy and upgrade houses in all the towns, maybe even marry one of your nameless, but quite attractive groupies...If you don't take this game (or life in general) too seriously, you will get the most out of it.Bottom line: A game with character and a lot of creative content, some (mostly technical) flaws, but nevertheless good entertainment; overall a 7/10."
,Recommended,288470,12124157,"Posted: 16 September, 2014",all,Bazgrim,"This game was a little rough at the start, I admit it.Lionhead seems to be taking quick action with the PC Game and listening to the community.Patches were deployed and the game is now PC friendly with mouse menu support and official workshop support.The artwork has been entirely redone, but not to the point where it doesn't feel like Fable.This game is for people who loved the Fable franchise and want to relive it in HD.If you're expecting an entirely new game, you're going to be sorely disappointed. The remake is well done and will make Fable have longer replayability for that much longer."
