’t own Fable Anniversary yet, play Fable:TLC and wait for a Steam sale to buy FA."
76561197985599207,Recommended,288470,31198320,Posted: 17 April,all,Canisgendered Translabradog,"This is the stuff memories are made of.For a long time, I decided against acquiring a remastered version of Fable. Having previously boughtFable: The Lost Chaptersa year after its' release, I saw no real advantage in buying what was essentially the same product a second time. But the call of nostalgia eventually got the better of me. That being said, objectivity obliges, I'll try not to drift too much down memory lane.Fable is the incarnation of Molyneux's vision in so many ways, it would be tedious to enumerate those aspects. It suffices to say that the game follows a pattern which was already present in Black & White: that of the choice between good and evil. But instead of playing as a god, you are a simple child who will grow to become a hero after a fateful, traumatising event. What kind of hero you will become - a good magician, sneaky fighter, etc.- is entirely of your choosing.Even down to its' very name, the world of Albion is a fantasy-folkloric rendition of medieval Britain. And it particularly excels in that area. The variety of English (mostly Northern and West Country) accents, Monty Pythonesquedialogue, landscapes, myths (e.g. Huw's longsword, King Arthur anyone?), creatures, map (which oddly ressembles Wales and the Irish Sea) are always there to remind you of the inherent Britishness of the game. From the bandit-ridden forestlands to the Ale-brewing taverns, it succeeds in creating an aesthetically pleasing rpg and is more-than-atmospheric-enough to bring about a credible world of its' own. To put it differently, Albion sure looks like a beautiful place to live in.Also worth noting is the musical score, the opening theme was composed by the ever so talented Danny Elfman (you might also remember him as the leading member of Oingo Boingo, the author of the Simpsons theme, Tim Burton movie soundtracks along with countless other film scores). Russell Shaw took great care of the rest, and much to his merit, one cannot understate the monumental influence of music in this game. It is literally the heart and soul of Fable.This game easily ranks up amongst the best titles to have graced the Xbox console. So what of this new version?Given that it is mainly a faithful reproduction of what was made a decade ago. There is very little in there to criticise.One of the main criticism I can bring up against Fable is that it is two-sided. Playing neutral won't really satisfy you. This game badly wants you to vouch for one side over the other. Either become a total♥♥♥♥♥♥or an angelic figure. On the other hand, playing evil is great fun (even hilarious at times). This system offers double-replayability down to the smallest side quest.What of the DLCs? Unless you seriously intend on looking like a total reincarnation of Jack of Blades at the end of the game, most of them aren't really worth buying. Of all the weapons featured in the game, only one will give you a true upper hand over your enemies (Solus Greatsword for the win), the DLC ones are no game-changers.As for the graphics, it's a bit of a mixed bag in my opinion. Sure, the landscape looks splendid. But the characters look too plastic, especially when it comes to their face, it's almost like something straight out ofSpitting Image. The original Xbox version had a charm of its own which this Anniversary edition can't surpass.All in all, these are minor flaws in contrast to the game as a whole. As someone who bears the unpopular opinion that Fable 2 was a downgrade and Fable 3 a slight improvement, I wish Lionhead studios had carried on the Fable franchise in the direction of the original game. Here's to hoping for a Fable IV reboot set in a prequel Old Kingdom world, much like I long for an Age of Empires IV (another franchise which Microsoft mindlessly destroyed).Highly recommended for first time players."
