76561198035580869,Recommended,288470,28193158,"Posted: 4 December, 2016",all,The Simon,"Most people I know got their introduction to the series with 2008's Fable II on the Xbox Tree-Sickidy. From what I remember, it's not a bad game, but it was a bit of a step down from the original. And the third and final entry was even worse. I believe Fable / Anniversary is the only truly great game in the series. Truly a one-hit wonder.Why? I guess it just has a charm that it's sequels did not possess (as much), from the characters to the world to the soundtrack. And the sequels were also too simplified, especially the last one, from the breadcrumb trails to the combat. Still, it's a shame Lionhead shut down recently, so there doesn't look to be a chance of a redemption for the series. Even the cancelled Fable Legends didn't look all that promising in my opinion.At least before Lionhead went out with a whimper, Anniversary was released, a remastered version of the original game. Being an Xbox hipster when all the other kids had PS2s, I played it back in 2005, not long after it's release. I remember actually not being too keen when I first started, what with starting as a kid and having to earn money to buy your sister a present. I thought, wow, how lacklustre is this... And the world and goofy-looking characters with thick-accents I found somewhat freaky.I didn't play it for long, and lent it to my brother to play at the hospital where he was staying with hella-bad tonsilitis. He played a ton of it and convinced me it was a great game, so I tried it again, and got very much into it, eventually falling in love with it. And I fell in love with it all over again with Anniversary.The world is a medieval interpretation of Britain, of course with the addition of magic and the threat of dark forces and whatnot. So yeah, sounds pretty darn familiar. But this exceeds with the way all that is portrayed. With colourful charm and humour, the choice between a good and bad alignment, either which alters you physically and changes the perception of those around you, and easy accessibility (but not too simple as it's sequels, as I said).You start as a little boy, scatting about your nice little town trying to get money to buy your sister a birthday present. And the choices start here. Do you earn that money with good deeds (i.e watch a bloke's barrels for him while goes off for a♥♥♥♥♥♥ or earn it with bad deeds? (agree to watch those barrels but then smash them and earn the approval of a little shitbag trying to peer pressure you). You get many of those choices throughout, some harder to make than others.Bandits attack your village, and♥♥♥♥♥♥goes sideways. You are rescued by a member of the Heroes Guild, where you begin training as said Hero, and grow up there, eventually leaving as an adult. As it goes in video games, whatever alignment you choose, you still end up saving the world from the big bad guy.In games with moral alignments, I tend to stay on the good side, because that's just me. And I did when I played the original. But this time round I became as evil as possible, doing bad deeds, assisting bandits, betraying my family and murdering innocents. Either side of the moral spectrum grants you exclusive items and weapons. I was so evil I grew horns, had red eyes and skin like a zombie. I looked awesome.On the higher end of the light side you have nice skin, a halo above your head, and all the people love you. And if someone loves you that much (you can further earn their affections with gifts and flirtatious gestures), you can ask them to marry you; man or woman. Pretty impossible to earn trust and affection if you're evil though. Everyone just screams and runs away. Just like me in real life ohhhhhh!All in all do I recommend this? You bet your big♥♥♥♥♥I do. The thing to take into consideration though, is that while this is an RPG, it's not entirely open-world. It consists of many individual chunks of areas, many with very narrow paths. And there isn't a colossal amount of things to do, once you've unlocked and collected everything. So those who are more used to the gargantuan games of today (i.e Skyrim, The Witcher 3) with literally hundreds of hours of content, stunning graphics and modern mechanics, might not be so impressed.But there is certainly enough to keep you going for a good 25+ hours or so. Especially now as it has achievements, and some rather amusing ones at that, like getting a headshot with a crossbow while dressed as a woman, farting while dressed as an assassin, and choosing whether to explore every single region or just get fat (they unlock the same achievement).A personal niggle from me? It's possible to miss one of the silver keys out of the thirty you can collect. If you leave it too long before starting the fishing competition, the NPC you talk to can disappear forever. As an achievement geek this♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥me off. You have to get all thirty keys in one playthrough for an achievement, and I have twenty-nine... So to get it again I'll have to start again and get the thirty all over again...Still, I gotta give it full marks for everything else.10/10"
,Not Recommended,288470,12077221,"Posted: 12 September, 2014",all,Artemisinin,"EDIT: It's worth noting that Lionhead have been good enough to update the game and have fixed many of the common gripes. This is good as it indicates that Lionhead are putting their money where their mouth is.However I still, honestly, believe that the incredible cost of this - around 3.5x more than the Fable: the Lost Chapters - makes this not worth it. At the end of the day it is, by and large, a ""HD"" redux of the original that doesn't look ""HD"" - Fable 3 looks notably better in everyway except the faces (which are done very well). With the mod support it has, maybe in time this will become a game that is worth the money it's asking for, however at the moment it is staggeringly overpriced.If you don't have the game, the cost of the other one is better.If you do have the game, the graphics are not actually that much better (or, really, that good to begin with - they use a DirectX package from 2010, and honestly, it looks like the game would fit that age quite well).[note: I use a 360 controller for many games anyway (the Fable series, in particular, does not need a mouse+key), so the pretty bad port mechanics aren't all that for me.]The big selling point of this game is the graphics and, based on the iffy model and texture quality, I highly doubt they're going to get noticeably better. In Oakvale there are areas that, graphically, look lifted from the base game.It looks like there will be mods (and if there can be mods there will be mods), but it also looks like there's some D1DLC.This is not worth $USD35; skip it and be happy."
