76561198297723126,Not Recommended,288470,30349217,Posted: 5 March,all,darkdisciple1313,"Only 1.4 hours with this version, but nearly 60 on the one I owned on my old computer (may it rest in pieces), so I can say now what I thought about the game then:The tl;dr version is simply: funny little game with a lot of wasted potential.Much longer version: I bought the lost chapters edition some years ago, played through it a few times as both good and evil characters, and mainly enjoyed my time. However, the game always seemed to be missing something, and with this new version, I realized what it was. Unlike many of the other RPGs I've played over the years, Fable never gave me this sense of nostalgia or longing to play it ever again once I deleted it off my older computer and put the box on the shelf.Fast forward to now, and the feeling remains the same. Sure, it's still a funny little game with some great moments to it, but I don't feel the same sense of wanting to play for hours at a time that I have with others in the genre. I've likely gotten spoiled with more modern games, but that's not just it. Fable always seems to hit a point where it is just on the edge of being a truly great game, but then falls short in far too many areas.My biggest gripe is with the alleged improvement in graphics. My computer is not a monster rig, but it plays most games well at high specs. With Fable Anniversary, I've had to mess with far too many things to get it to run properly in the manner in which it is supposed to be played. I can run it, but not at ultra-high specs, and that's just stupid for a game that's now eleven years old.The second gripe is with the combat, which was always my problem with the original version. The lock-on is terrible, especially when there are several enemies on the field of battle, which can lead to quick deaths if not properly managed in the first place. With the bad camera slinging around like a loose sail on a schooner during a hurricane, boss battles involving fast enemies can be nearly impossible to finish without dying numerous times, even on easier difficulties. The biggest problem, though, is when the battle is over...every time a dead enemy drops an orb, there's a really good chance that it will end up in a spot where you can't get to it (say, in a non-accessible water source), so you lose that power-up that round, even with the button that allows you to essentially vacu-suck them towards you.Finally, I just wish what had been improved had extended to more than just the graphics. Some new music would have been nice (all of it gets so bedamned redundant after the six thousandth repeat that I have to turn it off eventually), some re-voicing of the more squeaky little brats would have done my ears a favor, and some of the quests were just so dumb that I'd play them evil just to amuse myself.Fable was, for many, a failure because it never delivered on the developers' promises. I wouldn't have gone that far, but there was too much wasted potential for me to able to recommend it to any but those who enjoyed the game initially. New players will likely hate Fable, with all its improved graphics, and with good reason. It just doesn't stack up to more modern RPGs, from any country."
