,Not Recommended,288470,12079021,"Posted: 12 September, 2014",all,Commander Cuddles,"Bad Port, Terrible Controls, Same Old GameFable: The Lost Chapters was a wonderful game, but if you've already played it, you've already played this. This is nothing more than a high res texture/shader pack for Fable: TLC. This is not a full scale remake, leaving audio, animations and engine untouched. The character have been given higher detailed and higher resolution models, but they are stuck on the same old skeletons and use the same old animations. The worst offender are characters' eyes, which like the original game, still do not move. It looked weird 10 years ago, and it looks even weirder now. With the more realistic looking characters, with the old robotic movements, dead unmoving eyes, it really does give you the feeling of being trapped in some sort of fun house animatronic hell. The faces of the characters also feels like a downgrade from TLC, while they are higher resolution, most of the characters have rather ugly faces, and look a lot more generic than in TLC, losing a lot of their cartoonish look which gave them life in the first place.It's also a bad port directly from Xbox, with absolutely no attempt at making PC controls. This game is practically unplayable with a mouse and keyboard, even if that's how you typically played Fable: TLC in the past. In-game controls can be remapped (only once in game, NOT in the main menu) but all UI controls are ripped straight from xbox, meaning you have to type ""A"" ""B"" ""X"" ""Y"" on your keyboard in order to interact with the menus, and there is no option within the game to remap these. Other control flaws exist such as needing to press ""Insert"" and ""Delete"" to go to different pages in your inventory/journal.As for the environments and lighting changes, all is not well either. While a lot of the houses and scenery do look better with more detail than in TLC, the lighting kills the experience in a lot of places. They have in places put in some new real time lighting effects, but these are very localised. They look good if you are directly in that spot (in front of a fireplace for example) but look really out of place if you are viewing them from afar in an overall scene. You end up having a scene that is primarily ambient lighting, with a few spots of real time lighting that completely look out of place with the environment. You will end up with scenes like the Oakvale raid at the beginning of the game, where the scene is tinted heavily red, but the shadows and real time light sorces remain unshaded. It's hard to explain, but it ends up just looking very WRONG, like a badly photoshopped image.If this was a fan made free overhaul mod for the original game, or a forum collaboration (which is what it feels like) I would really be on board with all this, as a work in progress. But this is not fan made, this game had a team behind it and a budget. It is not free, it costs more than a lot of better games on steam at full price. And it is certainly not a work in progress, this is as good as it gets. And it's certainly far from good."
