,Not Recommended,288470,16917730,"Posted: 6 July, 2015",all,nathanwagenet,"I feel a little bad giving this a thumbs-down, because I don't strongly dislike it... but I probably wouldn't give it above about a 7.5/10, and to me, that deserves a thumbs down. I never played the original Fable games myself, but I remember seeing friends play them and they looked like they'd be a lot of fun, so when this went on sale a few weeks ago, I thought, ""Hey, I should check this out!""In some ways, I'm glad I did. I got 25 solid hours out of it, for $8.74—which is not great, but is also not bad. But then I hit a wall. I'm the kind of person who has to get all the achievements in every game I play. I played WoW for, like, three or four months (most of it during Mists of Pandaria) and got about 85% of the achievements that the entire game had to offer, to give you an idea of how I play games. And for most of the game, Fable was working just fine.But once I beat the game on the standard difficulty, I ran into some problems. There were a couple missing achievements (like beating Whisper without getting hurt) that I hadn't even noticed in time to get them on my original playthrough, so I figured I could just go through on Heroic and take care of those. I got that one, but found around the same time that hitting three enemies with a single flourish is essentially impossible to do on purpose, and I hadn't had it happen on accident throughout my entire Normal run. Likewise, there was the achievement for getting all the hero dolls that seems like it's going to be nearly impossible to do, without just sinking hours and hours into it in hopes of getting lucky. That's not how achievements should work, I'd say.And then there's Heroic difficulty. It started out just fine. I got through the training, ventured out to Bowerstone, did the first few quests, and then tried to make my way through Greatwood Lake. First I ran into an Earth Troll. ""Uh oh,"" I thought. ""This could be pretty difficult to beat on Heroic."" But with some careful dodging, I took it down—only to run into three bandits who had such an incredibly high amount of health that I couldn't even take *one* down with ALL of my MP into lightning AND all the crossbow firing I could get out before they caught up to me and killed me.Now, I don't think I'm bad at this game. I made it through Normal without EVER dying. But I tried this same spot of Heroic three or four times and had the same result each time, despite gaining some experience from each of the failed attempts before dying, and then using it to boost some of my stats. I would have had to spend an inordinate amount of time grinding experience to just get past three random bandits in Greatwood Lake, much less that first Balverine you come across in the swamp area. This seems like poor scaling to me, and essentially made me quit the game.It wasn't the only thing that pushed me in that direction, though. I thought the Good/Evil system was pretty good for a while. I went through all of Normal trying to make the most Good decisions possible, because I'm a good little boy. Then I found out that Good players just don't get as many options or as much good stuff as Evil players. It's quite limited, and I object to that design as well.All in all, this game does have quite a few things going for it, and it has an overall enjoyable game style. That's why I'd give it about a 7.5/10. But no higher."
