,Recommended,288470,17118426,"Posted: 18 July, 2015",all,Raum,"Fable is a decent enough game. Anyone who was playing on an Xbox in the very early 2000's knows how strangely disappointing this game was, due to good ol' Peter Molyneux and the Hype Train Express that he rides all over the place, but at the end of the day the game isn't necessarily bad. It is an enjoyable and simplistic RPG with a lot of great ideas that never really seem to be fully explored. It's the lack of exploration into these ideas that makes Fable strange, as there are truly a lot of really cool things in the game. It just feels a tad lackluster.Nonetheless, this is a great 15-20 hour RPG, worth playing at least once in my book. It's not very complicated, the combat is satisfying, and there are enough sidequests and hidden things to find to satiate most appetites. It is not an incredible or deep experience, but merely a game that is good-enough-to-pass-for-fun. There is an alignment system, you can give yourself tattoos or haircuts, you can run around on a murderous rampage if you feel the need, and you can walk around a town dancing and farting to please the locals. Go and get drunk in a bar, eat some apples, and beat up an innocent guy in town. Woo!For what it is worth, I've managed to beat the game three times, twice on the original Xbox and once just now on the PC. I've always enjoyed it, even if the game seems to come to an end a bit early.The PC port, as far as I could tell, was just fine. I liked being able to use a controller for this game, as I feel like it controls better on one. I didn't have any crashes or bugs, and it even alt-tabbed without a hitch. My six year old computer kept 60fps on all high details, as well. If you're looking for an interesting RPG to play through in 20 hours or less, Fable Anniversary would be a good choice."
