76561198027404826,Recommended,288470,12086910,"Posted: 13 September, 2014",all,Kadash Ispen,"Those of us that were old enough to play Fable: The Lost Chapter when it first came out on PC should be feeling a sense of serious deja vu, and not just because this is a remaster. Just like the original Fable, Lionhead hyped this game as much as they possibly could. At least this time, they didn't make tons of outlandish promises they couldn't keep. Instead they promised a remastering of on of their best games, and instead it's just sort of...updated a bit. Now, I can't play this game on anything but its lowest settings because I am poor, but the immediate reaction I had when starting the game was, ""What's wrong with the controls?"" And then I was immediately repulsed upon seeing the face of the hero as a child. In fact, the entire population of that beginning section has some serious facial issues that made me worry about the game. With the ugly models and the wonky controls, the first half hour isn't very enjoyable. Luckily, as you adapt to the new controls (or get a computer controller) and grow up, the character models settle into their skeletons and by the time you graduate from the guild, the game begins to show its true colors. While probably not deserving of the hype it got, neither does it deserve the immediate bashing. Are there problems? Yes, but the original Fable: The Lost Chapters on PC had plenty of problems itself and unlike the original, this one is going to have some modding support and possibly patching. Even on its lowest setting, post Guild Graduation, this game is a beautiful reconstruction of one of the greatest examples of RPGs ever released. Just calm down, keep an open mind, and enjoy it for what it is, Fable's Anniversary."
