,Recommended,288470,13558409,"Posted: 23 December, 2014",all,Atrum Ruina,"Fable Anniversary is exactly what it says on the tin: it's Fable: The Lost Chapters with a new coat of paint. The game looks good, performs great and, most importantly for me, has great controller support.A lot of the negative feedback for the game is based on the sorry state of its initial release. Most of these issues have been resolved in later builds, including adding mouse support, more logical keyboard inputs, better keymapping and better performance. I personally play the game with a controller and think the implemented support is superb however I can see how M+KB players would have been put off by the game's initial state.There are a few notable changes; Hero Saves are gone and replaced by a Checkpoint system. This has advantages in that it's much easier to pick up a mission where you left off, rather than having to plant yourself once a quest begins and hope nothing pulls you away. Unfortunately, some of the old exploits are now gone as a result of the change -- you can't decrease your age, you can't farm for experience by Hero Saving mid-mission, you can't get both of the ""either-or"" items in the game (Bright/Dark Will User's Hat, Sword of Aeons/Avo's Tear.) Overall, these were exploits so while I miss their inclusion, I don't think it's a straight negative for the game.In addition, the game now has a Fable 2/3 style control scheme. This works rather well, though it's largely not a significant advantage and comes with its own issues. You can't use your Fists since using X or Y (on a controller) automatically unsheathes your Sword or Bow, respectively. More importantly, Will users are significantly less flexible as they can now only use one spell at a time, having to cycle through each individual spell rather than cycling through groups of three and using a button to cast the appropriate spell. It's problematic and for most users, the Traditional is probably the best option. For users who focus almost entirely on Melee/Archery, however, it can be a boon.Overall, the game is faithful to the original and that's what you're buying -- the original game with enhanced graphics and Xinput support. I got the game on sale and think I got my money's worth, given that I'm a massive fan of the Fable franchise and the original is still arguably the best. A chance to replay the game with rose-colored glasses firmly in place is definitely worthwhile for me.P.S. Lipsyncing helps the dialog look a LOT less wooden. Very good move on Lionhead's part."
