76561198066983153,Recommended,288470,12656884,"Posted: 27 October, 2014",all,twin_beats,"Fable: The Lost Chapters has always been a favourite of mine and has a very special place in my heart. Fable Anniversary is, basically, exactly the same, but with several key differences.Let's start with the obvious: Textures have been massively reworked, giving wonderful eyecandy while preserving a Fable feel. That's the main selling point with Fable Anniversary. It really does look great, although I was a bit iffy about Chicken Chaser's new textures at first, but then I realized that, when he got old, he didn't exactly look old. And that was what I modded out with the original Fable, so that was an issue that I felt had been very well hurdled over (and I'm not the only one who wants their character to appear young for the game).And the not-so-obvious: The developers chose to keep the mouse out of the menu interface. And hey, that's not a bad thing, so long as it's done well. Unfortunately, it's not. With the layout of my computer, it took a fair amount of time to figure out how to properly traverse, and even then I was unable to move left in the prime categories due to the menu deciding I wanted to select instead of move left. Usually, these issues don't annoy me, but when I accidentally make a mistake by moving too quickly in the interface and go one more right than I had intended, so then I have to exit the menu to begin trade all over again, it begins to wear on the patience a little bit. In this case, the original's menu was much better with the layout, and it had the use of a mouse.The characters and environments, however, do look excellent. And while sometimes there can be minor issues in conversations (like mouths moving but no words coming out) and camera focusing for cutscenes, I personally can overlook it because of my love of the original game. I also enjoy hearing the original voices and am glad the developers chose to simply carry them over instead of get new voice actors. Then again, it's hard to replace someone like Maze or Jack of Blades.So, if you've ever played the original, I do suggest this game. The menu can be trying but I find it's worth it. And if you haven't jumped on the Fable bandwagon yet, this is a great game to start, so you can properly appreciate the lore in the sequel. But if you have the original game already and are iffy about purchasing, I'd suggest waiting for a sale. Believe me, you're only missing the pretty colours."
