76561198067773602,Recommended,288470,21146596,"Posted: 12 February, 2016",all,Jimnick,"7.5/10Fable aniversary in my eyes is an amazing game. But let me say first off, if you are looking for a remake of the original which changes gameplay elements in order to create an improvement of the game then this is not the game for you. But if you are just looking for practically the same game with different graphics or are new to the series then this game is perfect for you.Lets start off on what the game is, in fable aniversary you start off as a rosy cheeked child whos town gets slaughtered by bandits. After being saved by a hero he takes you to the Hero Guild where you tain and become a full fledged hero. You are now ready to traverse the world and chose who you will be, Good or evil.Now to start with the gameplay, Fable anniversary  is a combat heavy game which has a fairly simple system. You can use either will (magic) Finnese (Archery) or Strength (Melee). You are also able to block and dodge. Once you have learned how to do these mechanics the rest of the game will be fairly easy. In my playthroughs I have specced in each tree (you can upgrade all three) and I have seen that finnese is the most powerfull as all you need to do is roll then shoot then roll. Doing this I am rarely ever hit.Now the alignment system. Theres not much to say if you do a bad choice you gain bad points if do a good thing you get good points. It is a black and white shallow alignment system.Next is the equipment. Equipment in this game can be aquired unreasonabely fast. Not only can you gain money extremely quickly just by playing the game. If you use an exploit in the game you can quite literally max out your money in the first town. Meaning you can buy end game gear right after the first mission.Going on we have the skill progression. The game doesn't offer much in terms of skills rather you will upgrade your current skill and spell or get new spells. The way you gain skills is by earning experience, experience is earned by attacking enemies, for each hit you gain experience depending on how you hit them and when they die you gain general exp. General exp can be used on any skill whilst attack based exp can only be used on there tree. There is also an attack multiplier the more you hit without being hit means the more exp you get. Meaning playing an archer like I said above means you can get unimaginabley high amounts of exp from generic enemys. Ruining the game progression."
